[White "Chapter 1. 3.Nd2 c5 4.exd5 ex"]
[Black "6...exd4 7.Nxd4"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C09"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[PlyCount "34"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 {Doubtlessly the most flexible of White's three main
continuations on the move three,} 3. Nd2 {, known as the Tarrasch system, also
has a slight drawback: It obstructs the queen, reducing the pressure along the
d-file. This makes} c5 {a natural reply, but this is clearly not the final
commitment for Black, as after} 4. exd5 {he still has a relatively wide choice.
Over the past years, 4...Qxd5 has been very fashionable, but players wishing
to have some strategic plot in the centre (to which yours truly surely belongs)
will always prefer} exd5 {After White's neutral} 5. Ngf3 {Black again faces a
moment of decision. The optimal developing plan would be ...Nf6, ... Nc6, ...
Bd6, followed by castling. If allowed to carry it out, Black would reach very
comfortable play, but White can prevent it with Bb5 followed by 0-0, making
the e-file available for pressure against the black king. If 5...Nf6 6. Bb5+
the only viable answer is 6...Bd7, which has been one of Black's most popular
systems against the Tarrasch setup until recently. 5...a6!? is an interesting
attempt to develop the knights on the optimal squares at the cost of a tempo 
(which may be useful later anyway). There are some problems concerning the
move orders though. If White wants to avoid this line, he can play 4.Bb5+
followed by 5.Ngf3. Or if 3...a6 4.Ngf3 c5, he can already refrain from taking
on d5, because for practical reasons he is a tempo up in development and an
early clearance with ...cxd4 should favour him.} Nc6 {The classical treatment
of the French Isolani, advocated by Kortschnoj and Uhlmann in their best times.
For instance, in the years when I was making my first steps in tournament
chess, this was Kortschnoj's main and most reliable weapon during the final
Candidates' match with Karpov. He played it six times always reaching draws
without facing any special problems.} 6. Bb5 {The most active move, leaving
the e-file clear to prevent Black from developing his king's knight on the
best square with ...Nf6.} cxd4 $5 {This early exchange first came into the
limelight after Kortschnoj used it four times in his 1980 Candidates' final
against Huebner.} (6... Nf6 $6 7. O-O Be7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Qe2+ {will leave
Black with problems getting castled due to the pressure along the e-file.}) ({
The classical move order, used among others by Kortschnoj himself against the
match mentioned above with Karpov, is} 6... Bd6 {At that time the move order
was not considered that important, but there is a small detail:} 7. dxc5 $1 (7.
O-O cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nge7 {would transpose to any of lines 2 to 6 below.}) 7...
Bxc5 8. O-O Nge7 9. Nb3 Bd6 {The point is that White is not forced to hurry to
place a knight on d4 and transposing to lines 2 to 6. One of the most
unpleasant lines with independent value is} (9... Bb6 {looks more active, but
the practice has shown that White retains an enduring plus by exchanging the
active bishop with} 10. Re1 O-O 11. Be3 $14) 10. Bd3 O-O 11. c3 h6 ({Necessary
as} 11... Bg4 $2 {runs into} 12. Bxh7+ Kxh7 13. Ng5+) 12. h3 Nf5 (12... Bf5 $5
$14) 13. Bc2 {followed by Qd3.}) 7. Nxd4 {This natural move, seemingly putting
early pressure on Black, allows him to develop with ... Nf6, as the d4-knight
will be hanging soon, forcing White to lose a tempo and thus to neglect the
e-file pressure.} (7. O-O Bd6 {and}) (7. Qe2+ Qe7 {are examined later in the
database.}) 7... Bd7 8. N2f3 ({White does not get much by starting play along
the e-file:} 8. Qe2+ Be7 {As mentioned above, the d4-knight is hanging now.} 9.
N2f3 {This tempo loss allows Black to complete his development unhindered.} (9.
Bxc6 {is the only way to avoid losing a tempo, but it strengthens Black's
centre, offering him additional possibilities.} bxc6 10. O-O c5 11. N4f3 Nf6
12. Re1 h6 {Preparing ...Be6.} 13. b4 $5 (13. c4 Be6 14. cxd5 Nxd5 $11 {
offers Black active play and two great bishops in an open position, at least
compensating for the minor structural problem.}) 13... cxb4 14. Bb2 Be6 15. Nd4
O-O 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Qxe6+ Rf7 18. Nf3 Qd6 $11) 9... Nf6 10. O-O O-O 11. Bxc6
bxc6 12. Ne5 Bd6 $15 {Black has an advantage in the centre and the c6-pawn is
not edible.} (12... Rc8 13. Qa6 Qb6 14. Qxb6 axb6 15. Bg5 Rfd8 16. Rfe1 Kf8 17.
Nxd7+ Rxd7 18. Nf5 Bd8 19. Rad1 h6 20. Be3 c5 $11 {Svidler,P (2713)-Kramnik,V 
(2751) ICC (blitz) 1999 (1/2-1/2, 42)}) 13. Nexc6 $6 (13. Ndxc6 $2 Qe8 $19)
13... Qb6 (13... Bxc6 14. Nxc6 Qc7 15. Nd4 Bxh2+ 16. Kh1 Rae8 17. Qd3 Bd6 18.
Nb5 Qb6 19. Nxd6 Qxd6 $15) 14. Qb5 Rfc8 $17) (8. N2b3 Nf6 9. O-O Be7 10. Bf4
O-O 11. Bd3 (11. Be2 Re8 12. c3 {Dolmatov,S (2495)-Bjork,C (2200) Graz 1978 (1/
2-1/2, 18)} Bf8 13. Re1 Qb6 14. Qc2 Re4 15. Bg5 Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Rae8 $11) 11...
Nxd4 (11... Re8 12. Re1 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qb6 14. Rb1 Bc5 $11) 12. Nxd4 Qb6 13. Nb3
{Nevednichy,V (2548)-Sedina,E (2393) Saint Vincent 2004 (1/2-1/2, 46)} (13. Rb1
Bg4 14. Qd2 Ne4 $11) 13... a5 14. a4 Rfe8 15. c3 Bf8 16. Bc2 Bd6 17. Bxd6 Qxd6
18. Nd4 Ng4 19. Nf3 Ne5 20. Nxe5 Rxe5 $11 {Black's activity along the e-file
and the potential weakness on a4 (especially relevant in the ending)
compensate for the relative weakness of the isolani.}) 8... Nf6 9. O-O Be7 10.
h3 {Restricting Black's minor pieces.} (10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Ne5 Rc8 12. Nxd7 Qxd7
13. Qf3 {Adams,M (2715)-Vaisser,A (2549) France 2000 (1-0, 64)} Ne4 14. Nf5 Bf6
15. Rd1 Rd8 $11 {Defending the queen and preparing to castle without running
into Qxe4.}) (10. Re1 O-O 11. c3 Re8 12. Bg5 h6 13. Be3 Bd6 14. h3 a6 15. Bf1
Ne4 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Nd2 Bf5 18. Nxe4 Bxe4 19. Bd3 a5 20. Bxe4 Rxe4 $11 {
Huebner,R (2600)-Kortschnoj,V (2695) Merano 1980 (1/2-1/2, 34)}) (10. c3 O-O
11. Bd3 Bd6 $5 $146 12. Nf5 Bxf5 13. Bxf5 Re8 14. Bg5 (14. Be3 Bc7 15. Qb3 g6
16. Bh3 Na5 17. Qc2 Nc4 18. Bg5 Qd6) 14... h6 15. Bh4 g5 16. Bg3 Bxg3 17. hxg3
Qb6 $11) 10... O-O 11. Bd3 Re8 12. Bf4 Ne4 ({Black has another way of fighting
for the initiative:} 12... Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qb6 14. Rb1 (14. Nb3 a5 15. a4 Bd6 $11
) 14... Ne4 15. Be3 Qg6 16. f3 Bxh3 17. Qe2 Ng3 18. Qd2 Nf5 19. c3 Bd6 20. Bg5
(20. Rf2 Rxe3 21. Qxe3 Bh2+ 22. Kh1 Bg3 23. Qd2 Bxf2 24. Qxf2 Ng3+ 25. Kh2 Qxd3
$15) 20... Nxd4 21. Bxg6 Ne2+ 22. Kh1 Ng3+ 23. Kg1 $11) 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 (13...
bxc6 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Ne5 $14) 14. c3 (14. Be5 Qb6 15. Bd4 Bc5 16. Bxc5 Nxc5
17. Rb1 Nxd3 18. cxd3 d4 $15) 14... Bc5 15. Qc2 (15. Be5 Rc8 16. Bd4 Bd6 $11)
15... Qf6 16. Be3 {A necessary positional concession as otherwise Black's
pressure would become annoying.} (16. Bh2 Bd7 17. Qb3 (17. Qd1 Re7 $15) 17...
Bxh3 18. Qxd5 Rad8 19. Qc4 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 Qg6+ 21. Bg3 (21. Kh1 Rxd3 $19 22.
Qxd3 Nxf2+) 21... Bxf2 $19) 16... Bxe3 17. fxe3 Qh6 $15 {Haubro,M (2382)-Marin,
M (2579) Helsingor 2015 (1/2-1/2, 42)} *

