1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 cxd4 7. O-O {
The most flexible move, forcing Black to transpose to the classical main lines,
with the difference that White will have to spend a tempo on occupying the
d4-square with a knight soon.} Bd6 8. Nb3 Nge7 9. Nbxd4 O-O {This is the most
important tabiya of the classical French Isolani. White has tried many moves
and setups that require a separate investigation.} 10. c3 {The most natural
and popular move. WHite consolidates his control of d4 and clears the d1-a4
diagonal. Its drawback is that it allows Black's natural answer, helping him
to continue development freely.} Bg4 11. Qa4 Qd7 {A simple yet strong
developing move, connecting rooks and defending both c6 and g4. Besides, after
the planned a7-a6 the bishop has to retreat to e2, over defending f3, as
otherwise ...Nxd4 cannot be answered with Bxd7, when ...Nxf3!+ wins a piece.} (
{But there is nothing wrong with} 11... Bh5 {either, as accepting the pawn
sacrifice on c6 is dangerous.} 12. Bd3 (12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bxc6 Nxc6 14. Qxc6
Bxf3 15. gxf3 Rc8 16. Qa6 Rc4 $17 {with a strong attack.}) (12. Re1 Qc7 13. h3
Bg6 14. Bg5 a6 15. Bf1 {Karpov,A (2700)-Kortschnoj,V (2670) Moscow 1974 (1/2-1/
2, 51)} Be4 $5) (12. Be3 Qc7 13. h3 Na5 14. Bd3 Nc4 15. Nb5 Qd7 16. Bxc4 dxc4
17. Rfd1 Nf5 18. Qxc4 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Nxe3 20. fxe3 Qxh3 21. Nxd6 Qg3+ 22. Kf1
Qxf3+ 23. Ke1 Qg3+ {1/2-1/2 Karpov,A (2700)-Kortschnoj,V (2670) Moscow 1974})
12... h6 (12... Bc5 13. Re1 h6 14. Be3 Bb6 15. h3 Qd6 16. Be2 Rfe8 17. Rad1 Qf6
18. Nh2 Bxe2 19. Rxe2 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Qc6 21. Qxc6 bxc6 22. Rde1 Bxd4 23. cxd4
Kf8 $11 {Karpov,A (2700)-Kortschnoj,V (2670) Moscow 1974 (1/2-1/2, 30)}) 13.
Be3 a6 14. Rfe1 Qc7 15. h3 Na5 16. Nh4 Nc4 $11 {Karpov,A (2700)-Kortschnoj,V 
(2670) Moscow 1974 (1/2-1/2, 58)}) 12. Re1 (12. Bg5 a6 13. Be2 Rfe8 14. Rfe1
Ng6 15. Rad1 (15. h3 Nxd4 16. Qxd4 {Honigl,W-Vladimirov,Y Hallsberg 1975 (0-1,
30)} Re4 17. Qd3 Bxh3 $17 18. gxh3 Qxh3 19. Ne5 Qf5 $19) (15. Be3 $11) 15...
Re4 16. Qc2 Rae8 17. Be3 Bf4 18. Bd3 Nxd4 19. cxd4 Bxf3 20. gxf3 Qh3 $19 {
Gerhold,M (2240)-Uhlmann,W (2490) Wattens 1995 (0-1, 22)}) (12. Be3 a6 13. Be2
Nxd4 (13... Ng6 $11) 14. Qxd4 Nc6 15. Qd2 Rfe8 16. Rad1 Rad8 17. Bb6 Bc7 18.
Bxc7 Qxc7 19. Rfe1 h6 20. h3 Bf5 21. Bf1 Rxe1 22. Qxe1 Qb6 23. Rd2 Be4 {
Karpov, A (2700)-Kortschnoj,V (2670) Moscow 1974 (1/2-1/2, 67) Black's piece
pressure compensates for the isolani's relative weakness.}) 12... a6 13. Bxc6
Nxc6 ({Black usually avoids} 13... bxc6 14. Ne5 {even though White's advantage
is only symbolic:} Bxe5 15. Rxe5 Ng6 16. Re1 Rfe8 17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 18. Be3 Ne5)
14. Nxc6 (14. Be3 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Rae8 $15) (14. Qc2 Rae8 15. Bg5
f6 16. Bh4 Ne5 17. Bg3 Bh5 $15) 14... bxc6 15. Ne5 Bxe5 16. Rxe5 {Black has no
problems at all and the opposite-coloured bishops make a draw most likely.}
Rfe8 (16... f6 17. Re1 Rfe8 $11 {Chandler,M-Ost Hansen,J (2350) Haifa 1976 (1/
2-1/2, 41)}) 17. Rxe8+ Rxe8 18. Be3 Be2 19. Re1 Bb5 20. Qd1 Qf5 21. h3 h6 22.
Bd4 Rxe1+ 23. Qxe1 Qe4 $11 {Sebag,M (2414)-Michiels,B (2450) Hengelo 2004 (1/
2-1/2, 52)} *

