1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 cxd4 7. O-O Bd6 8.
Nb3 Nge7 9. Nbxd4 O-O 10. c3 Bg4 11. Be2 {A solid move, immediately removing
the pin and preparing to keep the blockade on d4 for a long time. On the other
hand, the last move also counts as a waste of time in the developing phase.}
Re8 {One should be aware of the usefulness of this move in several typical
situations. True, the e-file is not clear yet, but in some of the lines below
the pressure on e2 will restrict White's possibilities.} 12. Bg5 {The most
active move, preparing to exchange the dark-squared bishops with Bh4-g3.} (12.
Be3 Qd7 (12... Ng6 $11) 13. Re1 Rad8 14. Qd2 (14. Qc2 {Safin,S (2529)-Al
Modiahki,M (2492) Kolkata 2001 (1/2-1/2, 70)} Nf5 $5 15. Nxf5 Bxf5 16. Bd3 Be4
17. Ng5 f5 $132) 14... Bb8 15. Bf4 Bxf4 16. Qxf4 {White has managed exchanging
the bishops, but this cost him some time which Black has used to get perfectly
regrouped and ready to start the fight for the central squares.} Bxf3 (16...
Ng6 17. Qd2 Qc7 18. Bd3 Bxf3 19. Nxf3 Nce5 20. Nxe5 Rxe5 21. Rxe5 Qxe5 22. Re1
Qf6 {1/2-1/2 Geller,E-Botvinnik,M Wijk aan Zee 1969}) 17. Bxf3 (17. Nxf3 d4 $11
) 17... Ng6 18. Rxe8+ Qxe8 19. Qd2 Nge5 20. Be2 Nc4 $11) (12. h3 {can be
answered in two satisfactory ways:} Nxd4 $5 $146 {It appears that Black can
start fighting for the central squares at once, thanks to the time wasted by
White on Bb5-e2 and h2-h3.} (12... Bh5 {does not change either side's plans
much concerning other lines.} 13. Bg5 (13. Be3 Qd7 14. Qd2 Rad8 15. Rfe1 {
Shankar,R (2335)-Konguvel,P (2425) Kolkata 1997 (1/2-1/2, 34)} Bg6 16. Rad1 h6
17. Bf4 Nc8 18. Bd3 Be4 $11) 13... h6 14. Bxe7 Bxe7 15. Re1 Bf6 16. Qd2 Qb6 17.
Rad1 Nxd4 18. Nxd4 {1/2-1/2 Vogt,L (2450)-Uhlmann,W (2510) Leipzig 1982} Bg6 $5
) 13. Qxd4 (13. Nxd4 Bxe2 14. Nxe2 Nf5 15. Nd4 Nxd4 16. Qxd4 Re4 17. Qd3 Bc7
18. Be3 Qd6 19. g3 Qe6 20. Kg2 f5 $132) 13... Bf5 14. Bf4 Be4 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16.
Ng5 Bg6 17. Rad1 Nc6 18. Qd2 h6 19. Nf3 Be4 $11 {In these lines the usefulness
of ...Re8 is revealed more than once.}) (12. Re1 a6 {Defending b5 in order to
keep a white knight from b5 after the planned ...Qc7, but also inviting White
to commit himself.} (12... Qd7 13. Be3 {transposes to above.}) 13. Bg5 h6 14.
Bh4 Qb6 {Now that the bishop is far from e3, the queen becomes more ambitious.}
15. Qb3 Bc5 16. Qxb6 Bxb6 17. Bd3 Kf8 18. a3 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Bxd4 20. cxd4 Nf5
21. f3 Nxh4 22. fxg4 Ng6 23. g3 Ne7 24. Bf1 Nc6 $11 {Karpov,A (2700)
-Kortschnoj,V (2670) Moscow 1974 Candidates (1/2-1/2, 45)}) 12... h6 13. Bh4 (
13. Be3 {leads to play similar to 12.Be3, but ...h7-h6 is rather useful for
Black.} Ng6 (13... Qd7) 14. Qd2 Qf6 15. Rfe1 Nf4 16. Bf1 Re4 $36 17. Bd3 $2
Nxg2 $1 18. Bxe4 dxe4 19. Kxg2 exf3+ {0-1 Scotti,U (2250)-Guido,F (2320)
Montecatini Terme 1994}) (13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Re1 Qf6 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Nxf3 Rad8
$11) 13... Qb6 {Not the first and definitely not the last time when the queen
gets to this square, increasing the pressure on d4 but also simply attacking
b2.} 14. Qd2 (14. Bg3 {Fedorchuk,S (2650)-Vaisser,A (2522) Nice 2011 (1/2-1/2,
19)} Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Bxg3 16. hxg3 Qxb2 $15) 14... Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bxe2 16. Nxe2
Nf5 17. Bg3 Nxg3 18. hxg3 Rad8 (18... Re4 $5 $15) 19. Rfe1 {1/2-1/2 Forgo,E 
(2220)-Portisch,F (2410) Zalakaros 1992} *

