1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 cxd4 7. O-O Bd6 8.
Nb3 Nge7 9. Nbxd4 O-O 10. Be3 {A natural developing move, consolidating the
control over d4 but also committing and somewhat exposing the bishop.} Bg4 11.
Qd2 (11. h3 Nxd4 {forces White to occupy the d4-square with the bishop,
causing some instability.} 12. Bxd4 Bh5 13. Be2 (13. Re1 Nc6 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15.
Qd3 f6 16. Nh4 c5 17. Bc3 d4 18. Bd2 Bf7 19. Nf5 Qd7 20. c3 Bg6 21. Qc4+ Bf7
22. Qd3 Bg6 23. Qc4+ {1/2-1/2 Sokolov,A (2495)-Lputian,S (2540) Lvov 1984})
13... Nc6 14. Be3 Re8 15. Qd2 {Hawelko,M (2460)-Schmidt,W (2470) Wroslaw 1987 
(1-0, 39)} Qd7 16. Rad1 Rad8 17. Bg5 (17. c3 h6 18. Rfe1 Bc7 19. Nd4 Bxe2 20.
Rxe2 Re4 $11 {With optimal piece placement for Black.}) 17... f6 $5 {More
about this original move on Line 5. Here it serves concrete purposes, as the
bishop suddenly does not have good squares.} 18. Be3 (18. Bh4 $2 {is bad for
many reasons, as after h2-h3 the bishop's retreat to g3 is not favourable, but
Black could also use its absence from the initial diagonal with} Bf4 19. Qxf4
Rxe2 $17) 18... d4 19. Nxd4 Bxe2 20. Nxe2 Bh2+ $1 21. Kxh2 Qc7+ 22. Bf4 Rxd2
23. Bxc7 Rexe2 24. Rxd2 Rxd2 25. Rc1 Rxf2 26. Bg3 Re2 $11) (11. Be2 Re8 12. Qd2
Qd7 13. Rfe1 Rad8 14. Rad1 Bb8 15. Bf4 Bxf4 16. Qxf4 Ng6 17. Qd2 Re4 $11 {
Pavlov,M-Gulko,B Bucharest 1967 (0-1, 55)}) 11... a6 ({To my understanding
this is not a bit worse than the most popular move} 11... Qc7 12. h3 (12. g3 {
does not make much sense as it ensures the bishop's stability on g4.} Rad8 13.
Rfe1 Ng6 14. Bf1 {Martinovic,S (2460)-Kirov,N (2430) Pamporovo 1982 (1/2-1/2,
19)} Qd7 15. Bg2 Rfe8 $11 {With all the minor pieces on the board this is a
very good isolani version.}) 12... Bh5 13. Nh4 (13. Bd3 a6 14. c3 Rfe8 15. Rfe1
Na5 16. b3 Nac6 17. Rac1 {Neukirch,D (2345)-Uhlmann,W (2570) Goerlitz 1972 (1/
2-1/2, 25)} Rad8) 13... Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bf4 15. Be3 (15. Qd3 Nc6 16. Bc3 a6 17.
Ba4 d4 $132 18. Bxd4 b5 19. Bb3 Nxd4 20. Qxd4 Be5 $17) {Matulovic,M (2525)
-Jansa,V (2480) Tel Aviv 1964 (1-0, 39)} 15... Bh2+ 16. Kh1 Be5 17. c3 Qa5 18.
Bd3 d4 $11) 12. Be2 {Aiming at keeping both knights well defended.} (12. Bd3
Bc7 13. Bf4 Bb6 $11) 12... Bc7 $5 $146 (12... Qc7 {is the main move, but Black
has the time to set up the battery the other way around.}) 13. Rfe1 (13. Bf4
Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxf4 15. Qxf4 Bxe2 16. Nxe2 Qb6 $11) 13... Qd6 14. g3 Qd7 15. Bf4
(15. Rad1 Rad8 16. Nxc6 Nxc6 17. Nd4 Rfe8 18. Bxg4 Qxg4 19. Kg2 h5 $11) 15...
Ba5 $5 (15... Bb6 16. Nxc6 Nxc6 17. Ne5 Nxe5 18. Bxe5 $14) 16. c3 Rfe8 17. Bf1
Nxd4 18. Nxd4 Ng6 19. Bg2 (19. Be3 Ne5 $36) 19... Bb6 $11 {Black's minor
pieces exert sufficient pressure on White's key points.} *

