1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 cxd4 7. O-O Bd6 8.
Nb3 Nge7 9. Nbxd4 O-O 10. Bg5 {This is a more active way of developing the
bishop. In some cases White could play Bh4-g3, eliminating any danger along
the h2-b8 diagonal and exchanging the dark-squared bishops, thus increasing
his stability in the centre.} f6 $5 {Uhlmann introduced this move (and the
plan itself) in the game from the main line below. Apparently Black weakens
his kingside, but his idea is quite ambitious. He will soon play Ne5, reaching
central activity without allowing minor piece exchanges (as Nxe5 would
strengthen his centre). But in order to get a better feel for the position,
less committal continuations should also be examined:} (10... Qb6 {is the
typical way to combine pressure in the centre and on the queenside.} 11. Be3 (
11. Re1 Nxd4 $1 $146 12. Nxd4 Nc6 $15 {causes White to lose stability in the
centre.}) 11... Nxd4 (11... Bg4 $5 {is also worth considering as the
discovered attacks are not especially dangerous.}) 12. Nxd4 a6 13. Bd3 Qxb2 14.
Qh5 f5 15. Rab1 Qc3 16. f4 (16. Rfe1 Qc7 17. Nf3 b5 18. Bd2 Nc6 {Saulin,D 
(2462)-Sambuev,B (2380) Moscow 2001 (0-1, 27)}) 16... Qc7 17. Rf3 g6 18. Qh6
Nc6 {Benda,H (2329)-Baumegger,S (2411) Oberwart 2005 (0-1, 34) In both games
White had just reasonable compensation for the pawn, but not more.}) ({If
Black does not feel like grabbing the pawn he could choose also} 10... Qc7 11.
h3 h6 12. Bxe7 {There is no way to g3 for the bishop anymore and retreating to
e3 would mean losing a tempo.} Bxe7 13. c3 Bf6 {Black has an active minor
piece display and can look into the future with optimism.} 14. Re1 Qb6 (14...
Na5 15. Qe2 a6 16. Bd3 Bd7 17. Rad1 Rfe8 18. Qc2 Nc4 19. Bh7+ Kh8 20. Bf5 Rac8
21. Bxd7 Qxd7 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. Re1 g6 24. Kf1 Kg7 25. Re2 Re4 26. Qd3 Qe7 27.
b3 Nd6 $11 {Lutikov,A (2390)-Gulko,B (2565) Moscow 1982 (0-1, 59)}) 15. Bxc6 $2
(15. Qd3 Bd7 $11) 15... bxc6 16. Qd2 c5 17. Ne2 Bb7 $15 {Kaufman,L (2400)
-Byrne,R (2560) New York 1972 (0-1, 52)}) 11. Be3 ({As so many other times} 11.
Bh4 {leaves the centre and the queenside vulnerable to} Qb6 $1 12. Re1 $2 (12.
c3 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Be5 14. Ba4 Qxb2 15. Qd3 Qa3 16. Bc2 Ng6 17. Bg3 Bd7 {and
White's compensation is not entirely obvious.}) 12... Nxd4 $19 13. Nxd4 Ng6 14.
Bg3 Be5 {Black simply wins a piece, Paoli,E (2265)-Bronstein,D (2540) Odessa
1976 (0-1, 20)}) 11... Ne5 12. Re1 a6 13. Bf1 (13. Ba4 {looks a bit more
active but does not change the evaluation of the position as safe for Black.}
Bg4 14. h3 Bh5 $1 {As revealed below the e6-square can be temporarily left
without defence.} 15. c3 (15. Ne6 $2 Qc8 $15 16. Nxf8 $2 Nxf3+ 17. gxf3 Qxh3
$19) 15... Qc7 16. Qe2 Rad8 17. Rad1 Qc8 $11 {Black is perfectly regrouped and
WHite has no obvious way of starting any concrete plan.}) 13... Kh8 14. h3 Bd7
15. c3 Rc8 16. a4 Re8 $11 {Black is well regrouped and very compact. In order
to start concrete play, White is required to exchange on e5, but this has
double-edged consequences.} 17. Nxe5 fxe5 18. Nf3 h6 19. a5 Rc6 {The position
is sharp and Black eventually obtained a decisive kingside attack in Geller,
E-Uhlmann,W Amsterdam 1970 (0-1, 47)} *

