1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 cxd4 7. O-O Bd6 8.
Nb3 Nge7 9. Nbxd4 O-O {In this line we will examine a series of less frequent
and less critical moves.} 10. h3 {With incomplete development, this
prophylactical move allows Black to start central counterplay immediately.} (
10. Bd3 {is also aimed at preventing Bg4, but has the similar drawback of
wasting time at an early stage. Besides, it also weakens the control over d4.}
Nxd4 (10... Bg4 $2 11. Bxh7+ Kxh7 12. Ng5+) 11. Nxd4 Nc6 12. Nf5 (12. Qh5 g6
13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Qh6 Be5 15. Bg5 {Rakhmangulova,A (2260)-Cosma,E (2324)
Braila 2016 (1/2-1/2, 41)} Qc7 $15) (12. Be3 Ne5 13. h3 a6 14. c3 {Skripchenko,
A (2420)-Cosma,E (2316) Riga 2017 (1/2-1/2, 23)} Bd7 15. Re1 Qf6) 12... Bxf5 (
12... Bc7 13. c3 g6 14. Nh6+ Kg7 15. Re1 Be6 $15 16. Ng4 h5 17. Bh6+ Kh7 18.
Bxf8 Bxg4 19. f3 Qh4 20. g3 Bxg3 $17) 13. Bxf5 Qf6 14. Qd3 g6 15. Bh3 Rad8 16.
g3 {Vajda,L (2597)-Cosma,E (2324) Medias 2016 (1-0, 45)} Rfe8 17. Bg2 (17. c3
d4 $15) (17. a3 Bc5 $11) 17... Nb4 18. Qd1 Qf5 19. c3 Nc2 20. Rb1 Na3 $11) (10.
Re1 Bg4 {only has independent value if White makes the positional concession}
11. Bxc6 (11. Be2 Re8 12. Be3 {[%emt 0:00:04] transposes to Line 10.Be3}) 11...
bxc6 12. c3 Qc7 13. h3 Bd7 14. Bg5 Ng6 15. Qc2 f6 16. Bd2 Ne5 17. Nh4 Rae8 (
17... Rfe8 18. Nhf5 Bf8 19. Rad1 c5 20. Ne2 c4 21. Nf4 Nd3 $1) 18. Nhf5 Bc5 19.
Rad1 Bb6 20. Bc1 c5 21. Ne2 (21. Nb3 Ba4) 21... Bc6 (21... c4 22. Nf4 g6 23.
Nh6+ Kg7 24. Nxd5 Nf3+ 25. gxf3 Qg3+ 26. Kh1 Bxf2 $19) 22. Nf4 Qd7 23. Ne3 d4
24. cxd4 cxd4 25. Nc4 Kh8 26. Nxb6 axb6 27. Nd3 {Dicu-Marin,M Bucarest (rapid)
2015 (0-1, 65)} Bf3 $3 28. gxf3 Nxf3+ 29. Kg2 Qb7 30. Kg3 h5 31. Re2 (31. Rg1
h4+ 32. Kg4 f5+ 33. Kh5 g5 34. Bxg5 Qf7+ 35. Kh6 Qh7#) 31... h4+ 32. Kg4 f5+
33. Kf4 g5#) (10. b3 {was played by a few strong players over the years but
has the essential drawback of weakening the c3-square, while the kingside
attacking chances are very questionable. In principle, even minor piece mass
exchange can favour Black as White will have a backward pawn on c2, as weak as
if not weaker than the isolani.} Bg4 11. Bb2 Qb6 12. Nxc6 (12. a4 Be5 13. Nxc6
Nxc6 14. Bxe5 Nxe5 15. Be2 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 {1/2-1/2 Krnic,Z-Uhlmann,W Vrsac 1973}
Nxf3+ 17. Qxf3 Rac8 $11) (12. Be2 Rad8 13. h3 Bh5 14. Qd2 Rfe8 15. Rad1 Bg6 16.
Rfe1 Bc5 17. Bf1 Be4 $11 {Gipslis,A-Kortschnoj,V Riga 1970 (0-1, 59)}) 12...
bxc6 13. Be2 (13. Bd3 h6 14. h3 Bh5 15. Be2 Rfe8 16. Re1 Bc5 17. Nd4 Bg6 $15 {
Shamkovich, L-Vaganian,R Sochi 1970 (1-0, 53)}) 13... Rfe8 14. Qd2 Ng6 15. Rae1
Qb4 16. Bc3 Qf4 17. Qxf4 Nxf4 18. Bd1 c5 19. g3 Ne6 $11 {Cappello,R (2405)
-Portisch,F (2475) Reggio Emilia 1979 (1/2-1/2, 39)}) 10... Nxd4 {Black
immediately starts the fight for the central squares, as White is not well
developed enough to keep full control.} 11. Nxd4 (11. Qxd4 Bf5 12. c3 (12. Bd3
Nc6 13. Qa4 Bxd3 14. cxd3 Re8 $11) 12... Be4 13. Ng5 Nf5 14. Qd1 Qf6 15. Re1 (
15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Qd5 Bc7 17. Bd7 Rad8 18. Qxf5 Qd6 19. g3 Qxd7 20. Qxe4 Qxh3
21. Qxb7 Bb6 22. Qf3 h5) 15... Bc5 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Rxe4 Bxf2+ 18. Kxf2 Qb6+
19. Be3 Qxb5 $11 {Tukmakov,V (2560)-Uhlmann,W (2530) Hastings 1972 (1/2-1/2,
25)}) 11... Bc7 12. Bd3 (12. Re1 Qd6 13. Nf3 Ng6 (13... Nc6 14. c3 Bd7) 14. Bd3
{Tiviakov,S (2656) -Panjwani,R (2432) Montreal 2014 (1-0, 50)} Bd7 15. c3 Rfe8
16. Be3 Re7 $36 {for instance} 17. Bxg6 Qxg6 18. Qxd5 Bxh3) 12... Qd6 13. g3 (
13. f4 {weakens the position too much to be a problem for Black.} Bb6 14. c3 (
14. Be3 Nc6 $11) 14... Bxd4+ 15. cxd4 Bf5 16. Bxf5 Nxf5 17. g4 Ng3 18. Rf3 Ne4
$17 {Saren, I-Uhlmann,W (2570) Aarhus 1971 (0-1, 40)}) (13. Nf3 Bd7 14. c3 Rfe8
15. Be3 (15. Qb3 Ng6 $15) 15... Nf5 $15) 13... Bb6 (13... Qf6 14. c3 {Mrva,M 
(2340) -Prandstetter,E (2400) Brno 1990 (1/2-1/2, 34)} Bb6 15. Be3 Nc6 $11) 14.
Be3 (14. c3 Bxd4 (14... Qf6 $11) 15. cxd4 Bxh3 16. Bxh7+ (16. Qh5 Bf5 17. Bxf5
g6 18. Bxg6 fxg6 19. Qg4 Nc6 $132) 16... Kxh7 17. Qh5+ Kg8 18. Qxh3 Qg6 19. Kg2
Nf5 20. Rh1 f6 $11 {The knight is slightly stronger than the bishop in this
structure, compensating for the minor inconvenients black's king might have to
endure.}) 14... Bxd4 15. Bxd4 Nc6 16. c3 Nxd4 17. cxd4 Qf6 18. h4 Bf5 $11 {
Sjugirov,S (2629)-Zvjaginsev,V (2659) Taganrog 2011 (1/2-1/2, 29)} *

