1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 cxd4 7. Qe2+ Qe7 8.
Nxd4 Qxe2+ {This position was reached in three games of the aforementioned
Kortschnoj-Huebner match. It is worth mentioning that the queen exchange does
not make things worse for Black strategically. The typical minor piece play
remains the same and in some lines his king can stay in the centre to sustain
the Isolani.} 9. Nxe2 ({This maintains the right to castle, but releases the
pressure in the centre, while} 9. Kxe2 {examined below does exactly the
opposite!}) {Freed of the worries around the c6-square, Black continued his
development with:} 9... Nf6 {, leading to interesting but rather balanced,
play.} 10. c3 Bc5 11. Nb3 Bb6 {Black has a comfortable development. Besides,
in the absence of queens he has no kingside worries.} 12. f3 {A solid and
strategically ambitious move, typical for Huebner. It restricts the f6-knight
at the cost of weakening the e3-square. Obviously, White will castle long.} (
12. O-O O-O {has been played in a few later games, without facing Black with
any special problems.} 13. Bf4 (13. Nbd4 Bd7 14. Bd3 Rfe8 15. Bg5 Ne5 16. Bc2
Ne4 17. Bf4 Nc4 18. Bc1 Re5 19. Rd1 Rae8 {Black's activity is overwhelming
even in the absence of queens.} 20. Bd3 R5e7 21. Kf1 Ne5 22. Bc2 {Kruchev,B 
(2289)-Khmelnitski,A (2492) Voronezh 2004 (0-1, 29)} Ng4 $1 23. f3 Nef2 24. Rd2
Bxd4 25. cxd4 Bb5 $19) 13... a6 14. Bd3 Re8 15. Ned4 Ne5 16. Bxe5 Rxe5 17. Rfe1
Rxe1+ 18. Rxe1 Bd7 19. Nf5 (19. Kf1 Re8 20. Rxe8+ Nxe8 21. Nf5 Kf8 {1/2-1/2
Fluvia Poyatos,J (2421)-Narciso Dublan,M (2529) Martinenc 2001}) 19... Bxf5 (
19... g6 20. Ne3 Re8 $11) 20. Bxf5 g6 21. Bd3 Kf8 22. h3 h5 23. Kf1 Re8 24.
Rxe8+ Kxe8 25. Nd2 Ke7 {1/2-1/2 Burnoiu,N (2419)-Vysochin,S (2531) Predeal 2006
}) 12... a6 13. Bd3 (13. Bxc6+ bxc6 {strengthens the black centre, allowing an
original king's development:} 14. Bg5 Nd7 15. O-O-O f6 16. Bf4 Ne5 17. Rhe1 Kd7
18. Ned4 Re8 19. Nc2 Kc7 $132) 13... O-O {Kortschnoj played this after roughly
30 minutes. According to Pachman, he must have been pondering whether it made
sense to allow Bg5 or not. His last move is entirely satisfactory, but there
are at least two worthy alternatives.} (13... h6 14. Bf4 O-O 15. O-O-O Re8 16.
Ned4 Nh5 17. Bd2 Ne5 18. Bc2 Nc4 19. Rhe1 Bd7 $132) (13... Ne5 14. Bc2 O-O 15.
Bg5 Nc4 16. Bxf6 (16. O-O-O Be3+ 17. Bxe3 Nxe3 18. Rdg1 Re8 $36) 16... gxf6 17.
O-O-O Ne3 18. Rd2 Nxg2 19. Rxd5 Re8 $132 {The queenside majority is not
threatening yet, while the black bishops may prove dangerous in connection
with the weakened white kingside.}) 14. Bg5 Nd7 15. O-O-O Nde5 16. Bc2 f6 17.
Bf4 Be6 {The setup based on ...f7-f6 combined with installing a knight on e5
is known from the main lines with 6...Bd6.} 18. Ned4 Bf7 19. Rhe1 Rfe8 20. Re2
(20. Nf5 {may be a bit more promising:} Nc4 21. Nd2 Nxd2 22. Bxd2 (22. Kxd2 d4
$1 $11) 22... Rad8 (22... d4 23. b3 $5 dxc3 $140 24. Rxe8+ Rxe8 25. Bxc3) 23.
h4 {with some pressure in both cases.}) 20... g6 $5 {Black does not allow the
knight jump for the second time. Kortschnoj does not mind creating some
apparent weaknesses in order to take the important f5 square under his control.
} (20... Rad8 21. Nf5 Kf8 22. Rde1 g6 23. Nfd4 Nxd4 24. Nxd4 Bxd4 25. cxd4 Nc6
26. Rxe8+ Rxe8 27. Bd6+ Kg8 28. Rxe8+ Bxe8 29. Bc5 $14 {This is a more active
version of a similar ending which could have arisen below.}) 21. Nxc6 $5 {
In order to make progress, White needs to exchange some minor pieces.} (21.
Rde1 Nxd4 22. Nxd4 Bxd4 23. cxd4 Nc6 {may be slightly more pleasant for White,
but should be safe for Black.}) 21... Nxc6 {Quite a safe move, leading to
equality.} ({Kortschnoj must have avoided the generally desirable} 21... bxc6 {
due to} 22. Rde1 {However, this is not especially promising for White:} c5 (
22... Nc4 23. Nd4 {offers White some initiative.}) 23. Bxe5 (23. h3 {, taking
the h-pawn out of the b6-bishop range, fails to offer chances of an advantage,
too:} a5 $5 24. Bxe5 fxe5 25. Rxe5 Rxe5 26. Rxe5 a4 27. Nd2 Bc7 28. Re7 Bf4 $44
29. Kd1 Rb8 30. b3 axb3 31. axb3 Ra8) 23... Rxe5 24. Rxe5 fxe5 25. Rxe5 Bc7 26.
Re2 c4 27. Nd4 Bxh2 $11 {The blockade on d4 is not too impressive, since Black
has the dark-squared bishop. In the long run, the kingside configuration may
well favour Black.}) 22. Rde1 Rxe2 23. Rxe2 d4 $1 $11 {Huebner,R (2600)
-Kortschnoj, V (2695) Merano 1980 (1/2-1/2, 35)} *

