1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 cxd4 7. Qe2+ Qe7 8.
Nxd4 Qxe2+ 9. Kxe2 {Keeping the pressure on c6 but requiring some later waste
of time to get the king into safety.} Bd7 10. Nxc6 $5 {When I faced this move
it came as a surprise to me, even though I understood that it could cause
Black no troubles.} (10. N2b3 {and}) (10. N2f3 {are usually played and will be
examined in the lines below.}) ({The other way of releasing the tension is at
least dangerous for White:} 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Re1 f6 12. Kf1+ Kf7 13. N2b3 (13.
c3 c5 14. N4f3 Ne7 15. Nb3 Ng6 16. Be3 Rc8 $15) 13... c5 14. Ne2 g5 $5 $15 15.
Rd1 Be6 16. f4 h6 17. Ng3 f5 $17) 10... bxc6 11. Ba6 {The most consistent move,
trying to immobilise the black queenside. My opponent seemed to be on his own
from an early stage, since he spent a lot of time on the next phase.} (11. Bd3
{To my taste, this is slightly premature. I would play} Bd6 {, keeping the
same kind of flexibility as in the game.} (11... f6 {[%cal Ge8f7]} 12. c4 Ne7
13. Rd1 Kf7 14. Nb3 Be6 15. Na5 {Sivuk,V (2491)-Shariyazdanov,A (2568)
Voronezh 2014 (1/2-1/2, 46), with some slight initiative.}) 12. Re1 Ne7 13. Nf3
f6 14. c4 Kf7 15. Kf1 Rhb8 16. Rb1 a5 17. h3 h5 18. Be3 Nf5 19. Bd2 g5 20. cxd5
cxd5 $36 {Duda,J (2707)-Rakhmanov,A (2663) Linares 2017 (1/2-1/2, 31)}) ({
The pressure along the a4-e8 diagonal set by} 11. Ba4 {is ineffective.} Nf6 12.
c4 (12. Re1 {prevents ...Bd6 followed by 0-0, but with the bishop on a4 Black
has} O-O-O $1 13. Kf1 Bd6 14. Nb3 Rde8 15. Be3 Kc7 $15) 12... Bc5 13. Rd1 O-O
14. cxd5 Rfe8+ 15. Kf1 cxd5 16. Bxd7 Nxd7 17. Nb3 Bb6 $11 18. Rxd5 Nf6 $44 {
[%cal Ga8c8,Gf6g4]}) 11... Bd6 {Delaying the decision regarding the knight's
development.} ({I was briefly considering to put my pawns into motion as soon
as possible with} 11... Rb8 12. Nb3 c5 {but thought it would be dangerous in
view of} 13. Re1 {Still, Black seems to be doing fine here, too.} Bd6 14. Kf1+
Ne7 15. Be3 d4 16. Bd2 O-O 17. Bf4 (17. c3 Nc6) 17... Bxf4 18. Rxe7 Bf5 19.
Rxa7 Bxc2 20. Nxc5 Bd6 $11) 12. Nb3 ({I planned to meet} 12. Re1 {with} Ne7 ({
I also thought of} 12... Nf6 $5 13. Kf1+ Kd8 $11 {[%cal Gh8e8] , but it looked
a bit too exotic to me.}) 13. Nb3 c5 (13... O-O 14. Be3 {followed by Bc5.}) 14.
Na5 O-O 15. Nb7 Bc8 16. Nxd6 Bxa6+ 17. Kd1 Ng6 $13) 12... Nf6 {There is no
reason to refrain from the most active knight development now.} 13. Be3 O-O 14.
f3 $8 {White needs to clear the f2-square for his king as soon as possible.} (
14. Rhe1 Rfe8 {[%cal Gc6c5] /\ ...c5} 15. Kf1 Bxh2 $5 16. g3 Bh3+ 17. Ke2 c5 {
Curiously, the bishop is not easy to trap.} 18. Kf3 (18. Kd2 $2 Ne4+ 19. Kc1 d4
$19) (18. Kd1 $2 d4 19. Bf4 Rxe1+ 20. Kxe1 Re8+ {/\ ...Ne4xf2 -+}) 18... c4 19.
Nd4 Re4 {/\ Rae8} 20. Rh1 $6 Ng4 {with a strong initiative.}) (14. Rad1 Rfe8 {
[%csl Ge2]}) 14... Bc8 {After a long thought I decided that the most urgent
need was to unblock the a-pawn.} (14... Rfe8 {is pointless now due to} 15. Kf2)
15. Bd3 {The only way to keep some tension.} (15. Bxc8 Rfxc8 {frees Black's
play at once.} 16. Bc5 Be5 17. c3 (17. Bd4 Bxd4 18. Nxd4 c5 19. Nf5 Kf8 $11)
17... Nd7 18. Bf2 a5 19. Nc5 Nxc5 20. Bxc5 Rab8 21. Rab1 Rb5 $11) 15... a5 {
I did not seriously consider any alternatives to this move, since I wanted to
weaken White's squares along the b-file and ensure the exchange of the
potentially bad bishop with ...Ba6. But at the same time the resulting
weakness of the b5-square will cause some micro problems. Black could have
safely played the same plan without the insertion of the moves a7-a5 and a2-a4.
} (15... Nd7 $5 16. Rhe1 ({The same reaction as in the game is insufficient:} 
16. Kf2 $6 c5 17. Bb5 d4 18. Bd2 Rb8 {The main differences are that the bishop
is not stable on b5 while the black a-pawn is not hanging.} 19. Be2 Ne5 $17)
16... a5 (16... c5 {is good, too, but less dangerous for White since after} 17.
Bb5 d4 {he has the regrouping} 18. Bf2 Ne5 19. Bg3 $11) 17. a4 Ba6 $11 {
transposes to 15...Nd7 16.Rhe1 above.}) 16. a4 ({I planned to meet} 16. Bc5 {
with} Re8+ 17. Kf2 Be5 18. c3 Nd7 {Indeed, Black has excellent play and it is
White already who needs to be careful:} 19. Ba3 (19. Bd4 a4 $17) 19... Bc7 20.
Rhe1 Ne5 21. Bc2 Ba6 22. Nc5 Bb6 23. Kg3 Bb5 $13) 16... Nd7 $1 {It may seem
that Black is retreating on all fronts, but in fact this is the continuation
of a harmonious regrouping. After f2-f3 the knight had little to do on f6. The
last move takes advantage of the previous clearance of the d7-square to make
White forget about his dreams of a blockade on c5.} 17. Kf2 (17. Rhe1 Ba6 {
transposes to 15...Nd7 16.Rhe1 above.}) 17... g6 $5 {The most difficult move
in the game.} ({The idea behind White's last move was to allow him to meet} 
17... Ba6 $6 {with} 18. Bf5 $1 {for instance} Ne5 19. Bc5 (19. Nxa5 $5) 19...
Bxc5+ 20. Nxc5 g6 21. Rhe1 $16) (17... c5 $6 18. Bb5 $16 {[%csl Ra5,Gb5] x b5,
/\xPa5}) 18. Rad1 Ba6 $11 {In the absence of the threat Nf5, this solves all
of Black's problems. Vovk,A (2619)-Marin,M (2580) Mamaia 2015 (1/2-1/2, 53)} *

