1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 cxd4 7. Qe2+ Qe7 8.
Nxd4 Qxe2+ 9. Kxe2 Bd7 10. N2b3 ({The same as in similar positions with queens
on the board (see Line 7), this is less usual and less consistent than} 10.
N2f3 {examined in the next line.}) 10... Bd6 (10... Nxd4+ 11. Nxd4 {would
transpose to 10.N2f3 Nxd4+ 11.Nxd4, examined in a sideline of the next Line.})
11. Be3 (11. Bg5 {practically invites Uhlmann's} f6 {(Compare with Line 5)} 12.
Bh4 (12. Be3 Nge7 13. Bd3 Nb4 14. Nc1 Kf7 15. c3 Nxd3 16. Nxd3 Rhe8 17. Kd2 Ng6
{[%cal Gg6e5,Ge5c4] Planning ...Ne5-c4.} 18. b3 Rac8 19. h3 a6 20. Rhe1 Nh4 $15
{McShane,L (2438)-Gdanski,J (2535) Germany 2000 (0-1, 85)}) 12... Nge7 13. c3
a6 14. Bd3 Ne5 15. Bg3 Kf7 {We see that with the queens off, f7-f6 has an
additional point. The king is both safe and close to the centre on f7.} 16. a4
Rac8 17. Rhd1 (17. Bc2 $5 h5) 17... h5 18. h4 Nxd3 19. Rxd3 (19. Bxd6 Nxb2 $19)
19... Bxg3 20. fxg3 (20. Rxg3 Ng6 21. Nf3 Rhe8+ 22. Kd2 Re4 $17) 20... Ng6 21.
Nd2 Ne5 22. Re3 Ng4 23. Rd3 Rhe8+ 24. Kf1 Re7 $15 {Shvayger,Y (2408)-Peptan,C 
(2394) Baku 2016 (1/2-1/2, 71)}) 11... Nf6 {As a general rule in the French
Isolani, Black should play ...Nf6 whenever this does not imply concrete risk.}
({But there is nothing wrong with} 11... Nge7 {, for instance} 12. Rad1 O-O 13.
c3 Rfe8 14. Kd2 a6 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Bd3 Ng6 17. Bc5 Bf4+ 18. Kc2 Ne5 19. Nd4
Nxd3 20. Kxd3 f6 21. g3 Be5 22. Rde1 Kf7 23. f3 Rab8 24. b3 (24. b4 h5 25. a4
g5 26. Re2 h4 $132) 24... Bxd4 (24... h5 $132) 25. Kxd4 Rxe1 26. Rxe1 Re8 27.
Rxe8 Kxe8 $11 {Frolov,A (2499)-Pulpan,J (2331) Litomysl 2015 (1-0, 40)}) 12. h3
(12. f3 {restricts the knight but weakens the e3-square.} O-O 13. Kf2 Rfe8 14.
Rad1 a6 15. Bd3 Ne5 16. Bf5 Nc4 17. Bc1 Be5 18. c3 a5 {Black has placed all
his minor pieces on optimal squares.} 19. Bxd7 Nxd7 20. Nb5 (20. a4 Ndb6 21.
Nc5 Rec8 22. Ndb3 Bd6 23. Nxb7 Bf8 $17 {traps the knight.}) 20... a4 21. N3d4
Nc5 (21... a3 $5 22. b3 Nb2 23. Bxb2 axb2 24. a4 Nc5 {[%cal Ge5f4,Gf4c1]
Planning ...Bf4-c1.} 25. g3 Re7 26. Rd2 Rae8 27. Kg2 Bxd4 28. Nxd4 Re3 29. Rxb2
Rxc3 30. Rd1 h5 $11) 22. Rhe1 {Brunner,L (2455)-Kaenel,H (2325) Switzerland
1993 (1/2-1/2, 55)} Ra5 $5 $11) 12... O-O 13. Rhe1 Rfe8 ({Now was a good
moment to force White into deciding his bishop:} 13... a6 14. Bd3 Ne5 15. Bf5 (
15. Bf4 $2 Nxd3 16. Bxd6 Nxe1 17. Bxf8 Nxg2 $17) 15... Ba4 $5 {The bishop does
not threaten much here, but it avoids being exchanged, leaving the white
bishop exposed to g7-g6.}) 14. Kf1 Ne4 15. Rad1 a6 ({Black's successful
