1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 cxd4 7. Qe2+ Qe7 8.
Nxd4 Qxe2+ 9. Kxe2 Bd7 10. N2f3 {This is the most natural and most popular
move. But Black has at least three viable continuations at his disposal. For
practical reasons it is worth getting familiar with all of them, in order to
be ready to choose according to the opponent's style or tournament situation.
Not the least, it is always useful to know the specific plans and ideas.} Nf6 {
This was Kortschnoj's first reaction against Huebner. Curiously, nobody has
ever tried this natural developing of the knight again except for a single
game at a lower level played in 2016. The impact of the White's tragedy at the
very end of the game must have been so strong that people tended to
overestimate his previous problems.} ({If Black intends to play for a draw in
a simple, just symbolically worse position, he can try} 10... Nxd4+ 11. Nxd4
Bc5 12. Rd1 ({After} 12. Be3 {, even under the changed circumstances there is
nothing wrong with} Bxd4 13. Bxd7+ Kxd7 14. Bxd4 f6 {though.} 15. Rhd1 Ne7 16.
c4 Ke6 17. cxd5+ Nxd5 18. Rd2 Rhd8 19. Kf3 Nb4 20. a3 Nc6 21. Re1+ Kf7 $11 {
Ravi,T (2345)-Dolmatov,S (2610) Kolkata 1996 (1/2-1/2, 29)}) 12... Ne7 {
Kortschnoj had prepared an obvious plan, aimed to reach an only symbolically
worse ending. The knight steps as close as possible to the d4-square, since
Black intends to exchange the white knight soon.} 13. Be3 Bxd4 14. Bxd7+ Kxd7
15. Rxd4 Rhc8 16. c3 Rc4 $1 {It is essential to either exchange one rook or
activate his own.} 17. Rad1 (17. Rd3 Kc6 18. f3 Ng6 {would offer Black active
play.}) 17... Rxd4 18. Bxd4 f6 (18... Nf5 19. c4 dxc4 20. Bxg7+ Kc6 21. Bc3 {
leads to interesting play but would hardly suit the match strategy. With black,
one should strive for safety and a peaceful result.}) 19. c4 $1 {The only
chance to prove the bishop's superiority over the knight. With the d5-pawn on
the board Black is absolutely safe.} (19. g4 Kc6 20. h4 Ng6 21. h5 Ne5 22. f3
b5 $11) (19. f4 Kc6 {[%cal Ge7f5]} 20. g4 h5 21. h3 hxg4 22. hxg4 Rh8 $132)
19... Kc6 20. cxd5+ Nxd5 {Huebner,R (2600)-Kortschnoj,V (2695) Merano 1980 The
game was later adjourned in a drawn position, but Huebner resigned the match
without resuming this and the next adjourned game. The first thing coming up
to my mind when I saw this position was Kortschnoj's comment after his second
game from his Bauio 1978 match with Karpov: "Karpov has heard somewhere that
in the endgame the bishop is stronger than a knight. Maybe in Leonid Stein's
hands it would be, but not in his!" I would add that things would be different
if White had the other bishop left!}) (10... Bd6 11. c3 (11. Rd1 {as played in
Jaracz,P (2490)-Gdanski,J (2535) Plock 2000 (1-0, 84) should be answered in
the same way with} Nf6) (11. Re1 $1 {The critical continuation, preventing
Black from completing his development most desirable. Since sooner or later
Black's best plan is based on Uhlmann's f7-f6, it makes sense to play it as
soon as possible, in order to keep the king close to the centre with ... Kf7.}
f6 12. Kf1+ Kf7 13. Be3 Nge7 $11 14. Rad1 Rhd8 15. c3 a6 16. Bd3 Ne5 17. h3
Rac8 18. Bc2 Nc4 19. Bc1 g6 20. Bd3 Ne5 21. Bc2 Nc4 22. Re2 Re8 23. Rde1 Nc6
$11 {Kasparov,S (2493)-Vysochin,S (2533) Wroclaw 2012 (1/2-1/2, 52)}) (11. Be3
Nge7 12. Rad1 a6 13. Ba4 {Jerez Perez,A (2386)-Granda Zuniga,J (2672) Escaldes
2016 (0-1, 46)} O-O 14. Rhe1 b5 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Bb3 a5 17. c3 b4 18. Nd4 Bd7
$11) 11... Nf6 ({As always} 11... Nge7 {is an alternative:} 12. h3 a6 13. Bd3
f6 14. Rd1 h5 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. c4 g5 17. cxd5 cxd5 18. Nd4 Kf7 19. Be3 Rhb8
20. b3 a5 21. a4 Be5 22. Rab1 Nc6 {Ma,Q (2606)-Short,N (2684) Auckland 2016 (1/
2-1/2, 33)}) 12. Re1 {Mista,A (2479)-Kortschnoj,V (2620) Warsaw 2005 (0-1, 55)
The simple} O-O {offers Black easy play:} 13. Kf1 Rfe8 14. Rxe8+ (14. Bg5 Ne4
15. Be3 a6 16. Nxc6 $6 bxc6 {[%cal Ga8a6]}) (14. Be3 a6 15. Bd3 Ng4 $132 16.
Nc2 $2 Nxh2+ 17. Nxh2 Bxh2 18. g3 Ne5 19. Rad1 Bh3+ 20. Ke2 h5 $17) 14... Rxe8
15. Bg5 Ne4 16. Be3 Bb8 $5 {[%cal Ge4d6,Gd6c4] possibly followed by ...Nd6-c4.}
) 11. Re1 O-O-O $5 {This seems to be the more logical folow-up of the previous
move.} (11... Nxd4+ {This corresponds to Kortschnoj's match policy of
simplifying the position as soon as possible, but also looks like a small
concession.} 12. Nxd4 O-O-O 13. Bg5 $5 (13. Bd3 {fails to pose Black any
problems:} Bc5 {Huebner,R (2600)-Kortschnoj,V (2695) Merano 1980 (0-1, 63)})
13... Re8+ (13... Bc5 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Bxd7+ Kxd7 16. Nb3 $14) 14. Kf1 Rxe1+
15. Rxe1 Ne4 16. Be3 Bc5 17. Bd3 Re8 {with just a symbolic advantage for White.
}) 12. Bf4 (12. Be3 Ng4 13. Bf4 Bc5 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Bg3 f6 17.
h3 Rhe8+ 18. Kf1 Nh6 $11) (12. Kf1 Bc5 13. c3 Rde8 {[%cal Gg5d8]} 14. Bf4 Nxd4
15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. Bxd7+ Kxd7 17. cxd4 Re4 $11) (12. Bg5 Bc5 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14.
c3 Rhe8+ 15. Kf1 Nxd4 16. Bxd7+ Kxd7 17. cxd4 Bb6 18. g3 Re4 $11 {Black's
activity compensates for the kingside weaknesses.}) (12. Bd3 Re8+ 13. Kf1 Rxe1+
14. Kxe1 Bc5 $11) 12... Nxd4+ 13. Nxd4 Bc5 14. Bxd7+ (14. Kd3 Bxd4 15. Bxd7+
Kxd7 16. Kxd4 Rc8 17. Kd3 Rhe8 18. f3 Kc6 19. Be5 (19. Rad1 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5,
Gc5e6]}) 19... Nd7 20. Bxg7 Nc5+ 21. Kd2 Rg8 $11) 14... Kxd7 15. Nf3 Ng4 (15...
Ne4 16. Ne5+ Ke7 17. f3 Nd6 18. Kf1 $16 {Jarvenpaa,J (2295)-Kekki,P (2348)
Helsinki 2016 (1/2-1/2, 46)}) (15... Rhe8+ 16. Ne5+ Kc7 17. Kf3 (17. Kf1 Bd6
$11) 17... Nh5 18. Bd2 Re6 19. Nd3 Bd6 $11) 16. Bg3 Rhe8+ 17. Kf1 Rxe1+ 18.
Rxe1 f6 19. h3 Nh6 $11 *

