1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Bb5+ ({This early check can
transpose to the main lines after having avoided} 5. Ngf3 a6 {, but it can
also have independent value.}) 5... Nc6 6. Ne2 ({This way of developing the
knight is not too threatening. For the more popular} 6. Qe2+ {see the next
lines.}) 6... Nf6 {Since there is no danger of a check along the e-file Black
can develop his knight on the best square.} 7. O-O Bd6 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Nb3 Bb6
10. Ned4 {The only way of questioning Black's move order. But the practice has
shown that Black can sacrifice a pawn to evacuate his king immediately. Other
moves allow Black to complete his development comfortably.} (10. Bg5 O-O 11.
Ng3 (11. Nc3 h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 $11 13. Qxd5 Rd8 14. Qh5 Bf5 $36) (11. c3 a6 12.
Bd3 h6 13. Bh4 Bg4 14. h3 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Re8 16. Qd2 Qd6 $11) 11... h6 12. Bxf6
Qxf6 13. Qxd5 Be6 14. Qe4 Qxb2 15. Bd3 g6 $17 {Schmid,H (2260)-Dittmar,P (2349)
Seefeld 2002 (1/2-1/2, 54)}) (10. a4 O-O 11. Bxc6 (11. Bf4 {Ivanovic,B (2480)
-Dizdar,G (2455) Sarajevo 1983 (1/2-1/2, 42)} Bg4 12. h3 Bh5 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14.
a5 Bc7 $11) 11... bxc6 12. a5 Bc7 13. Bf4 Re8 (13... Ba6 14. Bxc7 Qxc7 15. Nc5
Bxe2 16. Qxe2 Rfe8 17. Qd3 Ne4 $11 {Prandstetter,E (2395)-Schmidt,W (2440)
Prague 1988 (1/2-1/2, 22)}) 14. Bxc7 Qxc7 $11 15. Nc5 $2 Qe7 $1 $19) 10... O-O
11. Bxc6 ({The other way to take the pawn just asks for trouble:} 11. Nxc6 bxc6
12. Bxc6 Ng4 13. g3 Nxf2 $1 14. Qxd5 (14. Rxf2 Qf6 $19) {Yudasin,L (2405)
-Vaganian,R (2550) Telavi 1982 (0-1, 45)} 14... Qe7 15. Bxa8 Qe2 16. Be3 Bxe3
17. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 18. Kh1 Qxc2 $17) 11... bxc6 12. Nxc6 Qd6 13. Ncd4 Ng4 14. g3 {
With Black's queen's bishop unchallenged on the light squares this forced
weakening weights a lot in the overall evaluation.} Qg6 {Not the only good
move.} (14... Qf6 15. Bf4 g5 16. Bc1 (16. f3 {Hresc,V (2355)-Kostic,V (2307)
Wattens 1988 (0-1, 36)} Nxh2 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18. Kxh2 Kh8 $17) 16... a5 17. a4
Re8 18. h3 Ne5 19. Qh5 h6 $15 20. Be3 Ba6 21. Rfe1 (21. Nb5 Bxb5 22. axb5 d4
$19) 21... Nc4 $15) 15. Bf4 (15. f3 Ne5 16. Re1 Nc4 17. c3 {Berelowitsch,A 
(2505)-Miezis,N (2481) Cairo 2000 (1/2-1/2, 36)} Qh5 $5 {Black has strong
pressure, making it difficult for White to complete his development.}) 15...
