1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Bb5+ Nc6 6. Qe2+ $5 {With this
move order White temporarily wins a pawn, hoping that Black will need making
some concession to retrieve it. In some lines White castles long, but this is
double-edged as the king is not entirely safe on the queenside.} Be7 7. dxc5
Nf6 8. Nb3 O-O 9. Be3 ({For the slightly more consistent} 9. Nf3 {see the next
line.}) {Black has tried many move orders, but since White has somewhat
deviated from the natural development, now is a good moment to spend a tempo
on forcing him to take a decision regarding the b5 bishop with} 9... a6 $5 10.
Bd3 (10. Bxc6 $6 bxc6 {The exchange on c6 allows Black to consolidate the
centre and starting active counterplay with ...a7-a5 followed by ...Ba6. This
will also make White's extra pawn vulnerable.} 11. Nf3 a5 {Maybe White should
be looking for a forcing way to maintain approximate equality such as} 12. Ne5
(12. O-O-O {Ambitious but risky.} a4 13. Nbd4 Qc7 14. Bg5 Bxc5 15. Bxf6 Qf4+ $1
16. Qd2 Qxf6 17. Qc3 Qd6 18. a3 Bg4 19. Rd2 Rfe8 $17 {Illingworth,M (2434)
-Cheng,B (2433) Melbourne 2014 (1-0, 52)}) 12... Qc7 13. Nd3 (13. Bf4 Re8 14.
Nd3 Qa7 15. O-O a4 16. Nd2 Bxc5 17. Qd1 {(0-1, 78) Faure,J (2200)-Toshkov,T 
(2450) Geneve 1989} a3 $17 18. b3 Bd4 19. Rb1 Bg4 20. Nf3 Ne4 $19) 13... a4 14.
Nd4 Ba6 15. O-O Bxc5 16. Ne6 fxe6 17. Bxc5 Rfe8 18. f4 Nd7 19. Qe3 e5 20. fxe5
Bxd3 21. cxd3 Qxe5 22. Qxe5 {1/2-1/2 Melia,S (2473)-Javakhishvili,L (2486)
Tbilisi 2015}) (10. Ba4 Re8 11. O-O-O {offers Black at least two satisfactory
continuations.} (11. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:16] transposes to Line}) 11... Ne4 {
is more complex.} (11... Bd7 {is a simple way to exchange the bishops and
reach comfortable equality but no more.} 12. Nf3 Qc7 (12... Nb8 13. Bxd7 Nbxd7
14. Nfd4 Nxc5 {1/2-1/2 Tatai,S (2460)-Uhlmann,W (2530) Skopje 1972}) 13. Qd2
Nb8 14. Bxd7 Nbxd7 15. Nfd4 Nxc5 16. Nf5 Nxb3+ 17. axb3 {Olafsson,H (2425)
