{[#]Facing the threat ...h5-h4, on his last move White decided to take the
daring pawn with 21.Qxh5. What had Black prepared against it?} 21... Nf3+ $1 {
This combination, less simple as it may seem at first sight, retrieves the
pawn yielding a positional advantage.} 22. Nxf3 Rxe1+ 23. Kh2 {White seems to
have survived the first wave of attack rather well. The e1-rook is hanging and
he also threatens Bg5 attacking all black major pieces, thus retrieving the
exchange by force.} (23. Nxe1 $2 {is impossible due to} Qxf2+ 24. Kh2 Qg1#)
23... g6 $1 (23... Rxc1 {is premature due to} 24. Rxc1 Bxf2 25. Rf1 {with
white initiative.}) 24. Qh6 Rxc1 $1 {With the white queen on h6 this works out
well.} 25. Qxc1 ({The point is that after} 25. Rxc1 Bxf2 $17 {Black has time
to consolidate his positional advantage, depriving his bishops' pair and the
weakness on e3, as} 26. Rf1 {runs into} Be3) 25... Bxf2 26. Qc2 Ba7 $17 {
Haag,E-Kortschnoj,V Gyula 1965 (0-1, 37)} *

