{[#]Black has advanced his pawns on both wings and now he should think of a
concrete decision before White could exploit his weaknesses on the light
squares.} 23... Bc3 $1 {This square was just crying out for the bishop. The
queen will now have a very narrow space available.} (23... f3 24. gxf3 (24.
Bxf3 $2 Rxf3 25. gxf3 Qg3+ 26. Kh1 Qxh3+ 27. Kg1 Rf8 $5) 24... Rad8 $15 {
is also promising but not immediately winning.}) 24. Qe2 (24. Qc1 Rad8 $5 {
would leave the white queen and d1-rook passive for quite a while.}) 24... f3
$1 {This is an improved version of the thematical break.} 25. Qe3 (25. gxf3 $2
Rae8 {[%csl Re2] traps the queen.}) 25... Rae8 26. Qc5 Qxc5 27. Nxc5 fxg2 28.
Kxg2 h5 $1 {Starting to tend a deadly net around the bishop.} 29. Bd7 Nf4+ 30.
Kg1 Re7 {The bishop has no moves available and with the knight unstable on c5
winning it is a question of time. 0-1 Neukirch,D-Uhlmann,W Potsdam 1974.} *

