{[#]White has just offered the bishops' exchange. How would you react with
Black?} 15... Bd7 $1 {This paradoxical move, keeping the supposedly "bad"
bishop is the strongest. In fact, the two bishops collaborate well to keep the
enemy kingside under pressure and also cause the queen some discomfort to find
a good square.} (15... Bxd3 $6 16. Qxd3 Rad8 17. Rad1 {allowed White to set up
some permament pressure, as his kingside was safe and the queen stable.} h6 18.
Re2 Ng6 19. g3 Be7 20. Nbd4 Bf6 21. Nf5 $14 {Rodriguez Cespedes,A-Uhlmann,W 
(2530) Berlin East 1979 (½-½, 40)}) (15... Bg4 $2 16. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 17. Ng5+)
16. Qd2 (16. h3 Nc8 $5 (16... Rad8 17. Bc2 g6 18. Qd2 Bf4) 17. Bc2 Nb6 18. Qd3
g6 $11 {[%cal Gb6c4,Gb6a4] and Black may play ...Nc4 or ...Na4 soon.}) 16...
Rad8 17. Rad1 (17. g3 Bg4 18. Nbd4 Nc6 19. Bf5 Bxf3 20. Nxf3 d4 $1 $11) 17...
Bf4 18. Qc2 Bg4 19. Nbd4 Nc6 $5 20. Bxh7+ Kh8 21. Bf5 Nxd4 22. cxd4 Bxf3 23.
Qxc7 Bxc7 24. gxf3 g6 *

