{[#]This is a typical derivation from the French Isolani, after the exchanges .
..Bxe3, fxe3 and Bxc6, ...bxc6. Both sides have weakneses but the possibility
of a blockade on c5 is a vital issue. How could Black take over the control?} 
15... Ba6 $1 {Black uses his "bad" bishop to unblock the central pawns.} 16.
Nf5 (16. Rfe1 Bc4 {is similar.}) 16... Nxf5 17. Rxf5 Bc4 $1 18. Rf3 Rfe8 $5 {
[%cal Gb6g1] Before playing ...c6-c5, Black wishes to make the most out of the
pressure along the g1-a7 diagonal.} 19. Rg3 (19. Qd4 f6 $5 $15 {parries any
kind of threats against g7 before breaking with ...c6-c5. For instance} 20. Rb1
c5 $1 21. Qxc5 Qxc5 22. Nxc5 Bxa2 23. Ra1 Rxb2) 19... g6 20. Rd1 c5 21. Rh3 a5
{Throwing the last queenside reserves into the attack.} 22. Qe1 a4 23. Nd2 Bxa2
$19 {Van der Wiel,J (2590)-Kortschnoj,V (2625) Brussels 1987 (0-1, 34)} *

