{[#]Black's position looks critical. White has a perfect knight on d4 and
attacking prospects along the back rank (for instance Qc8/f8 attacking the
rook followed by Re8). Can Black still fight for a draw?} 26... Rb6 $1 {
Not only attacking b2 but also removing the rook from the vulnerable square.}
27. Qe2 $6 (27. Qb8 $6 Be4 28. f3 Rxb2 29. fxe4 Qxc3 30. Rd1 Qe3+ 31. Kh2 dxe4
$132) ({White should have defended the pawn without giving up his attacking
ideas for good:} 27. Re2 $1 {In this case Black would have had a hard choice
between two lines offering him chances for a draw without a 100% sure verdict:}
Qa2 (27... Rxb2 28. Rxb2 Qxc3 29. Qe2 Qc1+ 30. Kh2 Qf4+ 31. g3 Qxd4 32. Rxb7
Qc5 $14 {The relative weakness of the white king and the strong pased pawn
offer some compensation for the exchange.}) 28. Qb8 Be4 29. f3 Rxb2 30. Rxb2
Qxb2 31. fxe4 Qxc3 32. Qe5 Qe3+ 33. Kh2 Qxe4 34. Qxe4+ dxe4 35. g4 Kg6 36. Kg3
h5 $14) 27... Qa2 $1 28. b3 Qxa3 {Black has won a pawn and the worst is
already behind. In Vorobiov,E (2544)-Vaganian,R (2623) Moscow 2004 (0-1, 41)
he even managed to win.} *

